Peru Stocks: Candente, Minsur, Scotiabank Peru, Southern Copper

-- B y   A l e x   E m e r y
-- 
2011-09-01T20:49:41Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-09-01/peru-stocks-candente-minsur-scotiabank-peru-southern-copper.html
The following companies had unusual
price changes in  Peru  trading. Stock symbols are in parentheses
and share prices are as of 4:10 p.m.  New York  time.  The  Lima  General Index fell 0.3 percent to 20,639.18. The
MSCI All Peru Capped Index gained 0.5 percent to 2,727.52.  Miners declined after metals slumped in New York and
 London , said  Daniel Romero , an analyst at Lima-based investment
fund NC&F Inversiones SA.  Rio Cristal Resources Corp. (RCZ)  , a Canadian zinc
exploration company, fell 5.9 percent to 16 cents.  Minsur SA (MINSURI1) 
(MINSURI1 PE), the world’s fourth-largest tin producer, dropped
1.5 percent to 3.35 soles.  Southern Copper Corp. (SCCO)  ,
Peru’s biggest copper producer, declined 1 percent to $33.36.
 Candente Copper Corp. (DNT)  , a Canadian exploration company,
slid 0.8 percent to $1.19.  Banking and industrial stocks gained after  Standard &
Poor’s  raised Peru’s foreign debt rating to BBB from BBB-,
Romero said.  Scotiabank Peru SA (SCOTIAC1)  (SCOTIAC1 PE), the local unit of
 Canada ’s third-largest bank, rose 5.1 percent to 48 soles after
earlier jumping as much as 29 percent as the company announced
the cut-off date for its regular dividend.  Intergroup Financial
Services Corp. (IFS)  , the owner of Peru’s fourth-largest
bank, Interbank, advanced 3.1 percent to $26.29.  Credicorp Ltd. (BAP) 
, Peru’s largest financial-services holding company,
gained 2.5 percent to $101.30. Corp. Aceros Arequipa SA
(CORAREI1 PE), the Lima-based steelmaker, rose 2 percent to 2.5
soles.  To contact the reporter on this story:
 Alex Emery  in Lima at 
 aemery1@bloomberg.net .  To contact the editor responsible for this story:
David Papadopoulos at 
 papadopoulos@bloomberg.net  